│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe provided IR causes opt --passes=slp-vectorizer  │
│ to abort with a malloc(): corrupted top size error. This strongly indicates a │
│ heap corruption (out-of-bounds write or excessive allocation) rather than a   │
│ logical assertion failure. The crash backtrace points into                    │
│ BoUpSLP::processBuildVector(), specifically the lambda TryPackScalars (frame  │
│ at line ~16250). That lambda manipulates SmallVector<Value*> Scalars and a    │
│ parallel mask vector (ReuseMask). If it writes beyond the allocated mask      │
│ storage or appends an absurd number of elements, the heap can be corrupted    │
│ leading to the later glibc abort.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows a │
│ gather node with 12 scalar values (select instructions). The vectorizer       │
│ computes a cost and a tree size reported as 6: \"Calculating cost for tree of │
│ size 6.\" This implies E->getVectorFactor() (VF) is 6 while E->Scalars.size() │
│ is 12 in this gather node. Later the vectorization tries to build a vector    │
│ for these 12 scalars using a VF of 6. That is an unusual but apparently       │
│ reachable configuration (vector factor smaller than number of gathered        │
│ scalars due to reuse/shuffle decisions). The first transformation happens     │
│ inside processBuildVector when constructing shuffle/gather patterns.\n\n3.    │
│ Root Cause Analysis:\nIn processBuildVector, the lambda TryPackScalars (lines │
│ 16243–16282 original) begins by unconditionally executing:\n                  │
│ Scalars.append(VF - Scalars.size(), PoisonValue::get(OrigScalarTy));\nThis    │
│ assumes VF >= Scalars.size(). In our reproducer VF == 6 and Scalars.size() == │
│ 12. Since both are unsigned, VF - Scalars.size() underflows, producing a very │
│ large unsigned value. SmallVector then tries to append that many PoisonValue  │
│ entries, corrupting memory (or triggering enormous allocation attempts). Even │
