│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The provided IR causes opt --passes=slp-vectorizer to abort with a malloc():  │
│ corrupted top size error. This strongly indicates a heap corruption           │
│ (out-of-bounds write or excessive allocation) rather than a logical assertion │
│ failure. The crash backtrace points into BoUpSLP::processBuildVector(),       │
│ specifically the lambda TryPackScalars (frame at line ~16250). That lambda    │
│ manipulates SmallVector<Value*> Scalars and a parallel mask vector            │
│ (ReuseMask). If it writes beyond the allocated mask storage or appends an     │
│ absurd number of elements, the heap can be corrupted leading to the later     │
│ glibc abort.                                                                  │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The log shows a gather node with 12 scalar values (select instructions). The  │
│ vectorizer computes a cost and a tree size reported as 6: "Calculating cost   │
│ for tree of size 6." This implies E->getVectorFactor() (VF) is 6 while        │
│ E->Scalars.size() is 12 in this gather node. Later the vectorization tries to │
│ build a vector for these 12 scalars using a VF of 6. That is an unusual but   │
│ apparently reachable configuration (vector factor smaller than number of      │
│ gathered scalars due to reuse/shuffle decisions). The first transformation    │
│ happens inside processBuildVector when constructing shuffle/gather patterns.  │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In processBuildVector, the lambda TryPackScalars (lines 16243–16282 original) │
│ begins by unconditionally executing:                                          │
│   Scalars.append(VF - Scalars.size(), PoisonValue::get(OrigScalarTy));        │
│ This assumes VF >= Scalars.size(). In our reproducer VF == 6 and              │
│ Scalars.size() == 12. Since both are unsigned, VF - Scalars.size()            │
│ underflows, producing a very large unsigned value. SmallVector then tries to  │
│ append that many PoisonValue entries, corrupting memory (or triggering        │
│ enormous allocation attempts). Even if Scalars.size() were only slightly      │
│ larger than VF, subsequent loops would write ReuseMask[I] for I >=            │
│ ReuseMask.size() (the mask is not resized after the append), causing          │
│ out-of-bounds writes. Thus the root cause is the missing guard ensuring VF >= │
│ Scalars.size() (an invariant that does not always hold) and failing to keep   │
│ ReuseMask sized consistently with Scalars after modification.                 │
│ The code earlier in processBuildVector conditionally pads when                │
│ GatheredScalars.size() != VF and size < VF, but there is no analogous         │
│ handling for size > VF. Hence TryPackScalars is invoked in an unsupported     │
│ state.                                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit lines 16243–16252 (definition start of TryPackScalars and the            │
│ unconditional append) to make appending conditional and to keep the ReuseMask │
│ vector in sync, avoiding unsigned underflow and mask overruns.                │
│ Concrete change:                                                              │
│ Replace the unconditional append line with guarded logic:                     │
│   if (Scalars.size() < VF) {                                                  │
│     unsigned OldSize = Scalars.size();                                        │
│     Scalars.append(VF - OldSize, PoisonValue::get(OrigScalarTy));             │
│     if (ReuseMask.size() < Scalars.size())                                    │
│       ReuseMask.resize(Scalars.size(), PoisonMaskElem);                       │
│   } else {                                                                    │
│     // VF < Scalars.size(): do not append; ensure mask covers all scalars.    │
│     if (ReuseMask.size() < Scalars.size())                                    │
│       ReuseMask.resize(Scalars.size(), PoisonMaskElem);                       │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ Optionally we could add a comment documenting that VF may be less than        │
│ Scalars.size() for certain gather reuse patterns and that later logic         │
│ iterates over full Scalars length.                                            │
│ This prevents underflow, huge allocation and mask OOB writes while preserving │
│ existing semantics for VF >= size.                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is due to unsigned underflow and subsequent memory corruption in    │
│ TryPackScalars when vector factor VF is smaller than the number of gathered   │
│ scalars. Adding a guard and synchronizing the mask vector fixes the heap      │
│ corruption without altering higher-level vectorization decisions. After this  │
│ patch, processBuildVector will safely handle cases where VF < Scalars.size(), │
│ eliminating the abort for the provided reproducer.                            │
│                                                                               │
